[[Image:Jonathan strange and mr norrell cover.jpg|200px|thumb|Black version of the first hardcover edition]]

'''''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell''''' is the first novel by British writer [[Susanna Clarke]]. An [[alternate history]] set in nineteenth-century England during the [[Napoleonic Wars]], it is  based on the premise that magic once existed in England and has returned with two men: Gilbert Norrell and Jonathan Strange. The novel concerns itself mostly with the relationship between these two men, but it also investigates the nature of "Englishness" and the boundary between reason and madness. It has been described as a [[fantasy]] novel, an alternate history, and an [[historical novel]].

The narrative draws on various [[Romanticism|Romantic]] literary traditions, such as the [[comedy of manners]], the [[Gothic fiction|Gothic tale]], and the [[Byronic hero]]. The novel's language is a [[pastiche]] of nineteenth-century writing styles, such as those of [[Jane Austen]] and [[Charles Dickens]]. Clarke describes the supernatural with mundane details and combines arch wit with antiquarian quaintness. She supplements the text with almost 200 footnotes, outlining the backstory and an entire [[Fictional books in the works of Susanna Clarke|fictional corpus of magical scholarship]].

Clarke began writing ''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell'' in 1993; ten years later she submitted the manuscript for publication. It was accepted by [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] and published in September 2004, with illustrations by [[Portia Rosenberg]]. Bloomsbury was so sure of its success that they printed 250,000 hardcover copies. The novel was well-received by critics and reached number three on the [[New York Times Best Seller list|''New York Times'' bestseller list]]. It was longlisted for the 2004 [[Booker Prize|Man Booker Prize]] and won the 2005 [[Hugo Award for Best Novel]].

==Plot summary==
