==Adaptations and sequel==

===Film===
On 15 October 2004, [[New Line Cinema]] announced that it had bought a three-year [[Option (filmmaking)|option]] on the film rights to ''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell''.<ref>Nigel Reynolds, [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1474242/Hollywood-buys-Harry-Potter-for-adults-film-rights.html "Hollywood buys 'Harry Potter for adults' film rights"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (16 October 2004). Retrieved 12 January 2009.</ref> Clarke received an unknown "seven-figure sum", making the deal "one of the biggest acquisitions of film rights for a book in recent years".<ref>Nic Hopkins, [http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/media/article496124.ece "New Line pays <U+00A3>1m for 'Strange' film option"], ''[[The Times]]'' (19 October 2004). Retrieved 12 January 2009.</ref> New Line chose [[Christopher Hampton]], whose adaptation of ''[[Dangerous Liaisons]]'' won an [[Academy Award]], to write it; New Line executives [[Mark Ordesky]] and [[Ileen Maisel]] were overseeing the production.<ref>Michael Fleming, [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117918806.html?categoryid=13&cs=1&query=%22jonathan+strange%22 "Scribe inks a 'Strange' deal"], ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (2 March 2005). Retrieved 12 January 2009.</ref> On 7 November 2005, ''The Daily Telegraph'' reported that Hampton had finished the first draft: "As you can imagine, it took a fair amount of time to work out some way to encapsulate that enormous book in a film of sensible length&nbsp;...&nbsp;[b]ut it was lots of fun <U+2013> and very unlike anything I have ever done before."<ref name=Christie>Nicola Christie, [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3647778/Sneak-preview-Otherwise-Engaged-and-Jonathan-Strange-and-Mr-Norrell.html "Sneak Preview: Otherwise Engaged and Jonathan Strange and Mr Norrell"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (7 November 2005). Retrieved 12 January 2009.</ref> At that time, no director or cast had yet been chosen.<ref name=Christie/> As of June 2006, Hampton was still working on the screenplay.<ref>Nicola Christie, "[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3653097/Sneak-preview-Maureen-Lipman-Jonathan-Strange-and-Mr-Norrell-Josh-Hartnett-and-more.html Sneak Preview: Maureen Lipman, Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell, Josh Hartnett and more"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (12 June 2006). Retrieved 12 January 2008.</ref>

===Audio book===
The 32-hour audio book of ''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell'' was released by [[Audio Renaissance]] in 2004.<ref name=SJH>S.J.H., "Review of ''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell''", ''AudioFile'' (Feb/Mar 2005) (subscription required). Retrieved 6 January 2009.</ref>  According to a review in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', reader [[Simon Prebble]] "navigates this production with much assuredness and an array of accents.&nbsp;...&nbsp;Prebble's full voice is altered to a delicate softness for young ladies of a certain breeding, or tightened to convey the snarkiness often heard in the costive Norrell."<ref>Rochelle O'Gorman, [http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2005/04/03/invention_and_detection_in_tales_thick_and_thin/ "Invention and Detection, In Tales Thick and 'Thin'"], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' (3 April 2005). Retrieved 12 January 2009.</ref> Prebble interrupts the main text to read the footnotes, announcing them with the word ''footnote''.<ref name=Newman>Andrew Adam Newman, "[http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/books/20audi.html?sq=&st=cse%22%20audio%20book=%22jonathan%20strange=&scp=1&pagewanted=all How Should a Book Sound? And What About Footnotes?"], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (20 January 2006). Retrieved 13 January 2009.</ref> According to the ''AudioFile'' review, the "narrative flow suffers" because of these interruptions and the reviewer recommends listening "with text in hand".<ref name=SJH/> Each note is on its own track, so listeners have the option of skipping them without missing text from the main narrative. When doing public readings, Clarke herself skips the notes.<ref name=Newman/>

===Sequel===
Clarke is currently working on a book that begins a few years after ''Jonathan Strange & Mr Norrell'' ends. It will center around characters such as Childermass and Vinculus who, as Clarke says, are "a bit lower down the social scale".<ref name=Silver1/>

